## Diagnosis

The `micro` mode was introduced as a progressive-disclosure pattern — shrink the label to fit the tile rather than hiding it. At 8px the text becomes illegible (below the ~11px legibility floor for screen fonts), so the "disclosure" is purely theatrical: the information is present in the DOM but not readable. This is worse than hiding it, because it gives a false impression of content density while delivering nothing to the user.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — Phantom Legibility**: rendering text at a size below the legibility threshold to preserve layout density. The content exists structurally but is perceptually absent, creating a false affordance.

The pattern typically appears when a component tries to handle every size tier with visible text instead of making a principled cut-off between "show label" and "hide label (use tooltip/aria-label)".

---

## Fix

### 1. Remove the `micro` size tier entirely

**`components/KnowledgeTreemap/KnowledgeTreemap.tsx`** (or wherever `TileLabel` / size-mode logic lives):

```tsx
// BEFORE — three tiers, one of which is illegible
type TileMode = 'micro' | 'compact' | 'full';

function getTileMode(width: number, height: number): TileMode {
  const area = width * height;
  if (width < 64) return 'micro';      // ← kills this
  if (area < 8000) return 'compact';
  return 'full';
}
```

```tsx
// AFTER — two tiers with a hard hide below the threshold
type TileMode = 'hidden' | 'compact' | 'full';

const LABEL_MIN_WIDTH  = 64;   // px — below this, label is not rendered
const LABEL_MIN_HEIGHT = 32;   // px — same rationale

function getTileMode(width: number, height: number): TileMode {
  if (width < LABEL_MIN_WIDTH || height < LABEL_MIN_HEIGHT) return 'hidden';
  if (width * height < 8000) return 'compact';
  return 'full';
}
```

### 2. Update the label renderer

```tsx
// BEFORE
function TileLabel({ name, mode }: { name: string; mode: TileMode }) {
  const sizeClass = {
    micro:   'text-[8px] leading-none',
    compact: 'text-xs leading-tight',
    full:    'text-sm leading-snug',
  }[mode];

  return <span className={`${sizeClass} truncate`}>{name}</span>;
}
```

```tsx
// AFTER — 'hidden' mode renders nothing visible but keeps the name
//          accessible via aria-label on the parent tile element
function TileLabel({ name, mode }: { name: string; mode: TileMode }) {
  if (mode === 'hidden') return null;

  const sizeClass = {
    compact: 'text-xs leading-tight',   // 12px — Tailwind default
    full:    'text-sm leading-snug',     // 14px
  }[mode];

  return <span className={`${sizeClass} truncate`}>{name}</span>;
}
```

### 3. Preserve accessibility on hidden-label tiles

The parent `<rect>` or `<g>` / `<div>` that wraps each tile must carry the name when the label is suppressed:

```tsx
// In your tile wrapper, wherever you map over nodes:
<div
  key={node.id}
  aria-label={node.name}          // ← always present
  title={node.name}               // ← native tooltip fallback
  style={{ width, height, ... }}
  className="relative overflow-hidden ..."
>
  <TileLabel name={node.name} mode={getTileMode(width, height)} />
</div>
```

This gives screen-reader users the full label and sighted users a pointer-hover tooltip — both are better than 8px text.

### 4. Verify your Tailwind safelist

If `text-[8px]` was added to a safelist to force Tailwind to emit it, remove it:

**`tailwind.config.ts`**:
```ts
// Remove any line like:
safelist: [
  'text-[8px]',   // ← delete
],
```

---

## Principle

> **Legibility is binary at the threshold.** A label either communicates or it doesn't. Text below ~11–12px on screen is below the perceptual legibility floor for most users and most rendering environments (subpixel hinting, display scaling, low-contrast themes). Do not scale type into illegibility to preserve structural presence — make a hard decision: show at minimum legible size, or hide and provide an alternative affordance (tooltip, aria-label, expand-on-hover). There is no design value in text that cannot be read.

The corollary for this system: **the smallest permitted text size in any rendered UI is `text-xs` (12px).** Anything requiring a smaller size is a layout signal that the element needs a different information architecture, not a smaller font.
